    "question_text": "Will all of these New England comic con events be held during 2026?",
    "probability": 0.94,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis of New England Comic Con Events for 2026\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\n\nToday is May 28, 2026. The three scheduled events are:\n- Rhode Island Anime Con (RIAC): June 6-7, 2026 (9 days away)\n- FAN EXPO Boston: August 7-9, 2026 (71 days away)\n- Rhode Island Comic Con (RICC): November 6-8, 2026 (162 days away)\n\nResolution is imminent for RIAC (in 9 days) and very near-term for FAN EXPO Boston.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\n\nAll three events should proceed as scheduled. None have been cancelled or postponed as of May 28, 2026. The events have confirmed dates, venues, and are actively promoting their 2026 editions.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n\nFor this to resolve NO, all three events must be cancelled or postponed such that they don't occur in 2026. This could happen through:\n- Natural disaster or major weather event affecting New England\n- Economic collapse impacting attendance and vendor participation\n- Unexpected shutdown/closure of venues (Rhode Island Convention Center, Boston venues)\n- Large-scale public health emergency\n- Mass organizer/operator bankruptcy\n- Unexpected permit or regulatory issues\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n\nAll three events proceed as currently scheduled. This is the baseline expectation given:\n- Events are only weeks to months away\n- No cancellations have been announced\n- Venues are operating normally\n- No force majeure events are imminent\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\nComic conventions in North America have a very high execution rate:\n- Large established conventions (San Diego Comic-Con, etc.) rarely cancel on short notice\n- Comic conventions have proven pandemic-resistant since 2021\n- Regional conventions like RICC and RIAC have established track records\n- FAN EXPO Boston is a major, well-established event with strong infrastructure\n- Historical cancellation rate for scheduled conventions this close to date: <2% (barring major systemic disruption)\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Supportive factors:**\n- We are already in May 2026 with no cancellations announced\n- RIAC is only 9 days away with no alerts\n- The articles cited in background are historical concerns (published prior to 2026) about industry-wide challenges, not specific threats to these 2026 events\n- All three events maintain active websites and promotional materials\n- No recent news indicates venue closure or organizer failure\n\n**Concerning factors:**\n- The background articles suggest broader comic con industry challenges (Hollywood pullback, attendance concerns, traffic/travel restrictions)\n- However, these are structural industry issues, not imminent cancellation triggers\n- No specific recent reporting indicates these three events face cancellation risk\n\n**Critical timing factor:**\n- With RIAC only 9 days away and no cancellation announced, the probability it proceeds is extremely high (>95%)\n- FAN EXPO Boston is 71 days away with no announced issues\n- Even RICC in November (162 days) has sufficient time to be confirmed\n\n## (g) Community prediction comparison\n\nNo explicit community prediction is provided in the prompt. I am proceeding with independent analysis based on fundamental principles.\n\n---\n\n## Reasoning Summary\n\nThis question has reached a critical timing point. We are literally days away from the first event (RIAC on June 6-7) with no cancellation announcement. In the modern event management environment, a convention scheduled for 9 days away without a cancellation announcement almost certainly proceeds.\n\nThe industry-wide concerns cited in the background materials are real structural issues but are not acute threats that would suddenly cancel these specific 2026 events at this late stage. If these events were facing cancellation, announcements would have come weeks or months prior.\n\nFor ALL three to be cancelled or postponed out of 2026:\n- RIAC would need to cancel in the next 9 days (extremely unlikely at this point)\n- AND FAN EXPO Boston would need to cancel in the next 71 days\n- AND RICC would need to cancel by November\n\nThe compound probability of all three failing becomes very low when any one is already weeks/months into the execution phase.\n\n**Probability: 94%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
