    "question_text": "Will the CBOE Volatility Index (VIX) close above 30 on more than 5 trading days between April 20, 2026 and May 31, 2026?",
    "probability": 0.05,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis of VIX >30 on >5 Trading Days (April 20 \u2013 May 31, 2026)\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nThe question window runs through May 31, 2026. As of May 28, 2026 (14:17), **3 trading days remain** (May 28, 29, 30, and potentially May 31 if a trading day). This is critical context: the vast majority of the observation period has already elapsed.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nWith only 3 calendar days left and the VIX currently at 16.29:\n- The VIX would need to spike above 30 on **more than 5 trading days between April 20 and May 31**\n- Given that we are at May 28 with 0 days above 30 in the last 30 days and the VIX at 16.29, the remaining window is extremely narrow\n- For YES to occur, the VIX would need to close above 30 on >5 days *already in the past* (April 20 \u2013 May 27), or rally sharply in the final 3 days and sustain it (which is impossible given the timeframe)\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome (most likely)\nThe VIX never reached >30 on more than 5 trading days during April 20 \u2013 May 31, 2026. This is the base case:\n- The U.S.\u2013Iran escalation that spiked VIX to 35.75 in early April de-escalated by late April\n- Markets repriced risk downward throughout May\n- The 30-day range of 16.29\u201319.5 and 0 days above 30 in the last 30 days indicate the stress episode is over\n- The final 3 trading days will not produce 5+ additional days above 30 (impossible mathematically)\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\nFor YES to resolve, the VIX must have closed above 30 on >5 days between April 20 and May 27 (the period already past). This would require:\n- A major shock during the April 20 \u2013 May 20 window that sustained VIX >30 for more than 5 trading days\n- Evidence: Historical records from late April\u2013early May would show spike(s) >30\n- Current VIX at 16.29 suggests any such spike has already normalized\n\nHowever, given that today is May 28 and the question window is essentially closed, **resolution depends entirely on historical data from April 20 \u2013 May 27**. The prompt's background notes a YTD high of 35.75 in \"early April,\" but no mention of sustained >30 readings in the April 20 \u2013 May 31 window specifically.\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 similar events\nHistorical base rates for VIX >30:\n- VIX >30 occurs roughly **10\u201315% of all trading days** during normal market conditions over a year\n- During acute geopolitical/financial stress, it clusters: VIX can exceed 30 for 5+ consecutive days (e.g., March 2020, August 2015, February 2018)\n- A threshold of \"more than 5 days in a 30-day window\" is not trivial; it requires either a sustained shock or multiple discrete shocks\n- Historically, VIX spikes above 30 are often brief (1\u20133 days); sustaining >30 for >5 days requires ongoing market stress\n\nFor a 30-trading-day window with no specific prior escalation, the base rate of having >5 days above 30 is roughly **20\u201330%** (i.e., VIX would need to be in a stress regime or face a fresh shock).\n\n## (f) How current data moves me from base rate\n\n**Critical insight: We are 3 days from resolution, and the observation period is nearly complete.**\n\nCurrent evidence strongly points to NO:\n1. **VIX at 16.29 (as of May 28)** \u2014 well below 30; no stress is evident now\n2. **0 days above 30 in the last 30 days** \u2014 suggests the early-April spike (35.75) was an isolated event that normalized quickly\n3. **30-day range 16.29\u201319.5** \u2014 tight range, no volatility spike evident in recent weeks\n4. **Background context**: The early-April U.S.\u2013Iran escalation spiked VIX to 35.75, but the question window starts April 20 (likely *after* that peak began to resolve)\n5. **Math constraint**: Only 3 trading days remain; even if VIX somehow spiked above 30 for all remaining days, that's only 3 days max, falling short of >5\n\n**Downward adjustment from base rate:**\n- Base rate (20\u201330%) assumes we're evaluating a future 30-day window with typical risks\n- We are now in the *final 3 days* of a window where only 0 days above 30 have occurred so far\n- The only way YES resolves is if >5 days above 30 occurred in April 20 \u2013 May 27 *and weren't part of the 30-day lookback* (which would show up in the 30-day stats)\n- The 30-day range and 0-day count strongly suggest this did NOT happen\n\n## (g) Community prediction comparison\nNo community prediction data provided. If forecasters were betting on YES early in the window, they would be anchoring on:\n- Base rate of ~20\u201330% for stress conditions\n- Uncertainty about April geopolitical trajectory\n\nHowever, with only 3 days left and clear market data showing no stress, any remaining YES forecasts would be heavily discounted. The live data (VIX 16.29, 0 days >30 in 30 days) is the strongest signal available.\n\n---\n\n## Reasoning Summary\nThe question hinge is whether the VIX closed above 30 on more than 5 trading days between April 20 and May 31, 2026. We are now at May 28 with only 3 days remaining. The critical observation:\n- **VIX is at 16.29** (well below 30)\n- **0 days above 30 in the last 30 days** (covering May 1\u201328)\n- **30-day range: 16.29\u201319.5** (narrow, no stress)\n\nThis data strongly implies that between April 20 and May 27, the VIX did **not** close above 30 on more than 5 days. The April 2 peak of 35.75 occurred before the April 20 window began, and the subsequent normalization is evident in the May price action.\n\nFor YES to resolve, we would need to see historical confirmation that 5+ days occurred April 20\u2013May 27. The live data (zero days above 30 in the last 30 days) makes this extremely unlikely. Even if there were a flash spike on May 28\u201330, we'd need evidence that it happened in the past window\u2014which the 30-day stats rule out.\n\n**Final confidence: NO is highly likely (~95%), YES is unlikely (~5%).**\n\n**Probability: 5%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_39432": {
    "question_id": 39432,
    "question_text": "Will Russia, India, and China hold a trilateral (three-way) meeting before September 1, 2026?",
    "probability": 0.28,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis: Will Russia, India, and China Hold a Trilateral Meeting Before September 1, 2026?\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nApproximately **3 months and 4 days** remain until the September 1, 2026 deadline.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nThe RIC format has been dormant at the leaders' level for years. The last confirmed trilateral leaders' meeting appears to have been in 2012. Without deliberate diplomatic effort, the status quo trajectory would be **continued dormancy** \u2014 the meeting does not occur.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- India and China remain focused on managing border tensions rather than trilateral coordination\n- India's multi-alignment strategy continues to pull it closer to the US-aligned bloc, making formal RIC revival diplomatically costly domestically\n- Russia-India relations remain warm but are secondary to India-US partnership concerns\n- Any meetings that do occur remain at Foreign Minister level rather than heads of government, or occur at margins of larger summits without formal trilateral structure\n- The three powers lack sufficient coordination incentive to schedule a dedicated meeting in this timeframe\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- Russia's recent diplomatic push for RIC revival gains traction, particularly if India sees strategic value in balancing geopolitical alignments\n- A window opens at a major multilateral summit (BRICS, SCO expansion, etc.) where all three leaders commit to and successfully execute a formal trilateral meeting\n- China and India's border situation stabilizes or is bracketed, reducing political sensitivity around India-China cooperation\n- The three capitals recognize mutual benefit in demonstrating non-Western solidarity and schedule a dedicated trilateral\n- A virtual/videoconference format is used to minimize logistics and political complications\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\n**RIC trilateral leaders meetings:**\n- Last confirmed: 2012 (14 years ago)\n- Prior history: Sporadic since early 2000s, perhaps 3-4 meetings at leaders' level in two decades\n- **Base rate: approximately 0.2 per year** (very infrequent)\n\n**Foreign Minister level RIC meetings:**\n- More frequent, occurring every few years\n- Approximately **0.5-1 per year on average**\n\n**Context:** The resolution criteria allow Foreign Minister-level meetings to count, which should increase the base rate materially.\n\n**For this specific timeframe (3 months):**\n- Given the historical dormancy and the short window, the base rate probability would be roughly **5-8%** if nothing changed\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Factors pushing UPWARD:**\n1. **Russia's active push:** The Diplomat article (cited in background) indicates Russia has recently pushed for RIC revival, suggesting diplomatic momentum\n2. **Forum activity:** Discussion of RIC revival at recent SCO and other summits shows the idea is active in diplomatic circles\n3. **Expanded resolution criteria:** Foreign Minister meetings count, not just leaders' meetings. This dramatically increases likelihood\n4. **Upcoming multilateral events:** With 3+ months remaining, multiple major summits (BRICS, SCO, EAS) will likely occur where a trilateral could be scheduled\n5. **Recent side huddles:** The 2025 SCO huddle (Putin-Modi-Xi) shows these leaders are willing to meet trilaterally informally; formalizing such a meeting seems plausible\n\n**Factors pushing DOWNWARD:**\n1. **India-China border tensions:** Persistent and unresolved; India remains cautious about appearing to side with China\n2. **India's strategic orientation:** Growing US alignment creates domestic political resistance to high-profile RIC participation\n3. **\"Informal\" precedent:** The pattern of side huddles at other summits suggests leaders prefer informal arrangements to formal trilateral declarations\n4. **Definition strictness:** Resolution requires explicit identification as \"trilateral/RIC\" in official communiques or two reputable news agencies \u2014 informal huddles explicitly don't count\n5. **14-year hiatus:** The 2012-2026 gap suggests institutional inertia is strong\n\n**Net adjustment from base rate:**\n- Foreign Minister level meetings are genuinely more likely given frequency patterns\n- Russia's recent push and diplomatic activity suggests elevated interest\n- The 3-month window with multiple upcoming multilaterals creates several opportunities\n- However, the strictness of resolution criteria (requiring explicit formal identification) filters out the informal huddles we know are happening\n\n**Adjusted probability: 20-25% for either leaders' or Foreign Minister trilateral meeting**\n\n## (g) Community prediction comparison\nI don't have access to existing community forecasts for this question. However, if community estimates lean toward the historical dormancy (sub-10%), I would diverge upward because:\n1. The inclusion of Foreign Minister meetings materially increases likelihood\n2. Russia's documented recent diplomatic push is new information suggesting changing baseline\n3. Multiple upcoming multilateral forums in the 3-month window create scheduling opportunities\n4. The explicit mention of \"RIC revival\" discussions in diplomatic circles suggests this is actively under consideration\n\n## Reasoning Summary\n\nThe question hinges on whether **any** trilateral (leaders OR foreign ministers) occurs in a formal, publicly acknowledged capacity. The base rate of RIC meetings is very low historically (~0.2 per year at leaders' level), but:\n\n- Foreign Minister meetings are more frequent and explicitly allowed\n- Russia's recent push for revival suggests genuine diplomatic movement\n- Multiple upcoming multilaterals (BRICS in autumn likely, SCO, others) will provide scheduling opportunities\n- However, India-China tensions and India's strategic caution create real friction\n- The formal/explicit requirement filters out the informal huddles we know happen\n\nThe 3-month remaining window is short but not negligible \u2014 it covers summer 2026 when major summits typically occur. Russia's documented advocacy for revival suggests this isn't zero-probability. The probability of at least a Foreign Minister-level trilateral occurring and being explicitly identified as such is meaningfully above the historical baseline but still notably below 50% given the persistent geopolitical headwinds.\n\n**Probability: 28%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_38463": {
    "question_id": 38463,
    "question_text": "Will computer science and engineering see a greater percentage decrease (or smaller increase) in the number of enrolled international students in Trump's first year compared to other fields?",
    "probability": 0.38,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis of International STEM Student Enrollment Question\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nThe question resolves when data for the 2025-26 academic year is released, expected in November 2026. Today is May 28, 2026, so we are approximately **5 months away from resolution**. The data should be released very soon.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nHistorically, Math & Computer Science and Engineering have grown faster than other fields. In 2023-24, these fields combined grew 10.8% while other fields grew 3.5%. If this trend continued unchanged, CS/Engineering would again grow faster than other fields, resolving to **NO**.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\nCS and Engineering continue their historical faster growth trajectory despite Trump administration policies. This could occur if:\n- Trump policies have limited impact on enrollment (delayed implementation, legal challenges)\n- Strong underlying demand for STEM education persists despite visa restrictions\n- Chinese and Indian students find ways around restrictions or alternative pathways\n- Buffering effect of existing multi-year programs continues\n- Restrictions disproportionately affect non-STEM fields (as Samotsvety noted regarding humanities)\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\nCS and Engineering enrollment decreases year-over-year or grows more slowly than other fields. This would require:\n- Trump visa policies to have material, immediate impact on new enrollments\n- State Department's May 2025 visa revocations for Chinese CS/engineering students to cascade\n- Chinese government restricting brain drain in high-demand tech fields\n- Social media screening and other barriers to deter international STEM applicants\n- Other fields showing surprising resilience or growth despite overall headwinds\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\nLooking at historical data in the table:\n- From 2022-23 to 2023-24: CS/Math grew 16.9%, Engineering grew 3.6% (combined ~10.8%), while other fields averaged 3.5% growth\n- In recent years, CS/Engineering have consistently outpaced other fields\n- The base rate for CS/Engineering underperforming other fields appears quite low, historically around 15-20%\n\nHowever, this is a new regime with unprecedented immigration restrictions specifically targeting STEM fields from China/India.\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Key developments since Trump's inauguration (Jan 20, 2025):**\n\n1. **May 2025 State Department directive**: Explicit targeting of Chinese students in \"critical fields\" including CS and engineering - this is a major policy shift directly addressing the fields in question\n\n2. **Timing dynamics**: The 2025-26 academic year (which the question measures) would have begun in Fall 2025, giving Trump's policies ~8 months to impact new enrollment decisions. This is significant lead time for policy effects.\n\n3. **Samotsvety's assessment (31% for faster decline in STEM)**: While the Samotsvety group estimated a 31% chance of faster STEM decline generally, they specifically cited reasons to expect CS/Engineering might be *more* resilient (buffering effect, strong brand, social media screening hurting humanities more).\n\n4. **Recent reporting**: The May 2025 visa policy specifically targeting Chinese students in CS fields directly contradicts the buffering argument - new policies are now explicitly targeting the highest-concentration student populations.\n\n5. **2024-25 data likely coming soon**: As of May 2026, we should have preliminary 2024-25 data (expected November 2025). This would give us insight into initial policy impacts before the 2025-26 data releases.\n\n## (g) Community prediction comparison\n\nThe question doesn't provide a direct community forecast, but Samotsvety's 31% for faster STEM decline broadly is relevant. However, Samotsvety explicitly argued that CS/Engineering would likely be *more* resilient than the STEM average because:\n- Stronger baseline demand\n- Buffering from existing students\n- Social media screening affecting humanities more\n\nThe May 2025 State Department policy specifically targeting Chinese CS/engineering students is **more restrictive than Samotsvety anticipated when they made their forecast**. This is a material change that should increase the YES probability above what a naive reading of their 31% would suggest.\n\n## Critical uncertainty factors:\n\n1. **Data release timing**: We're very close to November 2026 when data releases. Any preliminary or leaked data from IIE between now and then would be highly informative.\n\n2. **Definition of comparison**: The question requires CS/Engineering to underperform \"all other fields combined.\" If even one large field (like Business/Management) also declines sharply, this becomes harder.\n\n3. **Magnitude question**: Even if CS/Engineering growth slows, whether it underperforms depends on how severely other fields are affected.\n\n4. **Delayed effects**: Many 2025-26 enrollment decisions would have been made in 2024-25 academic year (before or early in Trump administration). Full policy effects might not appear until 2026-27.\n\n## Probability assessment:\n\n- **Base rate for underperformance**: ~20% (CS/Engineering historically outpace other fields)\n- **Adjustment for May 2025 visa restrictions**: +15% (explicit policy targeting CS from China/India)\n- **Adjustment for buffering effect uncertainty**: -5% (multi-year programs do provide protection)\n- **Adjustment for competitive dynamics**: +8% (China may restrict talent flows; other fields more resilient)\n- **Adjustment for timing/measurement specificity**: -3% (some effects may be lagged; other fields might also be hit)\n\nThe explicit May 2025 visa policy targeting Chinese CS students is a material factor that wasn't fully captured by Samotsvety's 31% estimate. However, there are still structural reasons to expect CS/Engineering to outperform (brand strength, buffering effects, continued high demand). The required outcome is that CS/Engineering underperform *all other fields*, not just grow more slowly.\n\n**Probability: 38%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_41544": {
    "question_id": 41544,
    "question_text": "Will Jonathan Ross be indicted or charged in the death of Renee Good before July 1, 2026?",
    "probability": 0.18,
    "reasoning": "I'll analyze this systematically before providing my probability estimate.\n\n(a) **Time left until resolution:**\nToday is May 28, 2026. The resolution deadline is July 1, 2026. This leaves approximately 34 days.\n\n(b) **Status quo outcome if nothing changes:**\nAs of late May 2026, no indictment or charge has been filed against Jonathan Ross. If the current trajectory continues without major legal developments, the question would resolve NO.\n\n(c) **Scenario for NO outcome:**\n- Federal and/or state prosecutors decline to prosecute or fail to bring charges within the 34-day window\n- Investigations conclude without formal charges\n- Legal proceedings continue beyond July 1, 2026\n- Charges are filed for lesser crimes (civil rights violations, etc.) rather than murder/manslaughter\n\n(d) **Scenario for YES outcome:**\n- A grand jury convenes and issues an indictment for murder or manslaughter\n- Prosecutors file formal charges for the unlawful killing/death of Renee Good\n- This occurs within the 34-day window (by June 30, 2026)\n\n(e) **Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur:**\nLooking at fatal police/federal officer shootings resulting in murder/manslaughter charges:\n- Federal agents (ICE, FBI, etc.) are very rarely charged with murder/manslaughter\n- Studies show law enforcement fatal shooting prosecutions occur in roughly 1-2% of cases nationally\n- When federal agents are involved (vs. local police), prosecution rates are even lower due to qualified immunity and federal law complexities\n- Of those prosecuted, murder/manslaughter charges are less common than civil rights violations\n\nBase rate for federal agent \u2192 murder/manslaughter charge: approximately 0.5-1%\n\n(f) **How current data/news moves me from base rate:**\n\n*Factors pushing toward YES:*\n- Strong visual evidence (body cam, bystander video) challenging the self-defense narrative\n- Significant political pressure and public outcry\n- Recent case (January 2026) with immediate investigation underway\n- Local/state level involvement alongside federal, potentially multiple paths to prosecution\n- Contested self-defense claim based on video evidence\n\n*Factors pushing toward NO:*\n- Only 34 days remain until deadline - very tight timeline for indictment\n- Prosecuting federal agents faces significant legal/institutional barriers (qualified immunity, federal vs state jurisdiction issues)\n- Federal prosecutors historically reluctant to charge ICE agents\n- Civil rights charges are more typical than murder/manslaughter charges\n- No reports of charges being imminent as of late May 2026\n- Complex jurisdiction questions (federal vs state prosecution)\n- Historical precedent: most similar cases don't result in murder/manslaughter charges, even with video evidence\n\nThe short timeframe is the critical constraint. Even with strong evidence and political pressure, moving from investigation to formal indictment in 34 days is compressed. Grand juries need time to convene, evidence needs formal presentation, and prosecutors need to build cases.\n\n(g) **Community prediction comparison:**\nI don't have access to current Metaculus or other forecaster predictions, but given the specificity of this case and the tight timeline, I would expect community predictions to reflect:\n- Recognition of strong visual evidence\n- Skepticism about federal agent prosecution timeline\n- Understanding of institutional barriers to charging federal officers\n- Likely clustering in the 10-25% range\n\nMy analysis suggests this warrants lower probability due to the 34-day constraint being extremely tight for grand jury process, despite the strong evidence.\n\n---\n\n**PROBABILITY: 18%**\n\n**Reasoning:** While the visual evidence is compelling and political pressure is significant, the 34-day timeframe creates a formidable procedural barrier. Grand jury convening, evidence presentation, deliberation, and formal indictment is a compressed schedule. Additionally, federal prosecutors face institutional incentives to avoid charging their own agencies' personnel with murder/manslaughter, preferring civil rights charges. The base rate for federal agent murder/manslaughter charges is very low. The strong visual evidence and public pressure push this above the baseline ~1%, but the tight deadline and institutional factors keep it well below 50%.",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_41219": {
    "question_id": 41219,
    "question_text": "Will Vivek Ramaswamy win the 2026 Ohio gubernatorial election?",
    "probability": 0.54,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis of 2026 Ohio Gubernatorial Election: Vivek Ramaswamy\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nThe general election is November 3, 2026. From today (May 28, 2026), there are approximately **5 months and 6 days** until resolution.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nIf the political situation remains static from today:\n- Ramaswamy has already won the Republican primary (May 5, 2026 has passed)\n- Recent polls show him in a tight race against Democratic nominee Amy Acton\n- The race appears to be a genuine toss-up rather than a Republican lock, despite Ohio's rightward shift\n- Status quo suggests a competitive general election with moderate Republican advantage\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- Democratic nominee Amy Acton gains momentum in the final 5 months\n- National political climate shifts against Republicans between now and November\n- Ramaswamy's record as a businessman/entrepreneur is effectively attacked by Democrats\n- Acton consolidates Democratic support and mobilizes key constituencies (urban voters, educated voters)\n- Turnout patterns favor Democrats relative to 2022/2024\n- Ramaswamy's lack of political experience becomes a liability in the general election campaign\n- DOGE departure/controversies continue to dog his campaign\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- Ramaswamy successfully leverages Trump endorsement and GOP establishment backing\n- Trump's continued popularity in Ohio translates to coattails for Ramaswamy\n- Ramaswamy's outsider, business-focused message resonates with Ohio voters over next 5 months\n- Republican turnout models hold or improve from 2022/2024 levels\n- Acton fails to overcome her relative obscurity compared to Ramaswamy's national profile\n- Economic conditions remain favorable or blamed on Biden/prior administrations\n- Ramaswamy outperforms polling through superior campaign organization\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\n**Incumbent party holding governorship:**\n- When the incumbent party's governor is term-limited and party is strong in the state, that party retains the seat approximately 70-75% of the time historically\n- Ohio is currently a strong Republican state with a trifecta/triplex\n\n**Challenging candidate specific factors:**\n- Business outsiders without political experience have mixed records in statewide races (40-50% win rates)\n- Trump-endorsed candidates in Trump-strong states have performed well (65-70% win rate in recent cycles)\n- Candidates with minimal political experience in their state face higher risk of losing despite strong party\n\n**General election dynamics in strong partisan states:**\n- In states where one party holds a 25+ point governor margin (DeWine 2022: +25), the party typically retains the seat 75%+ of the time\n- However, when polling shows a competitive race rather than a strong lead, the actual outcome tends to be closer to 50-50\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Data moving toward YES:**\n- Ohio shifted strongly Republican: Trump +11.2% in 2024, DeWine +25% in 2022 represent genuine rightward movement\n- Trump's endorsement carries significant weight in current Republican primary/general dynamics\n- Republican Party of Ohio endorsed Ramaswamy\n- Republican trifecta/triplex control suggests structural Republican advantage\n\n**Data moving toward NO:**\n- **Most critical:** Recent polling shows race is very close (essentially a toss-up), not a clear Republican lead\n- In strong Republican states, strong Republican candidates typically lead by 8-15 points at this stage; Ramaswamy's marginal lead is concerning for Republicans\n- Amy Acton has recently emerged as stronger than typical Democratic challengers (she held statewide health position during COVID)\n- 5 months remains for Democrats to define Ramaswamy as out-of-touch businessman\n- Ramaswamy's DOGE departure was embarrassing and shows instability\n- Ramaswamy has minimal Ohio political roots despite being born there\n\n**The polling is the critical anchor:** When a strong-party-state candidate is in a statistical tie 5 months out, historical win rate is roughly 45-55%, not 70-75%.\n\n## (g) If community prediction exists and differs >10%, explain why you diverge\n\nI don't have access to current Metaculus/prediction market data as of May 28, 2026, but I would expect prediction markets to price this in the 50-60% range for Ramaswamy given:\n- Ohio's Republican lean (should push up from 50%)\n- The actually-competitive polling (should pull down from 65-70%)\n\nIf markets show >65% for Ramaswamy, that would be overweighting the state partisanship relative to the actual current competitive polling. If <45%, that would be underweighting Republican structural advantages in Ohio.\n\n---\n\n## Probability Assessment\n\n**Key reasoning:**\n1. **Base rate for strong party in term-limited seat:** 70-75%, but...\n2. **Heavily discounted by competitive polling:** Ramaswamy's marginal lead in current polling is atypical for a strong Republican candidate in a Republican-lean state 5 months before the election\n3. **Ramaswamy-specific risks:** Minimal political experience, DOGE embarrassment, business-outsider vulnerability in general elections, limited Ohio roots\n4. **Ramaswamy-specific advantages:** Trump backing, national profile, business credentials may appeal to voters, Republican structural advantage in Ohio\n\nThe critical insight is that **polling showing a toss-up in a Republican-lean state is not the same as showing Republican strength.** When a Republican candidate is polling at statistical parity in Ohio 5 months before election day, historical performance suggests ~48-52% win rate, not 65-70%.\n\nThe Republican structural advantage in Ohio pushes this from 50% to approximately 55%, but the competitive polling prevents higher confidence.\n\n**Probability: 54%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_43501": {
    "question_id": 43501,
    "question_text": "Will any U.S. state or EU member state restrict large-scale data center grid connections before September 2026?",
    "probability": 0.96,
    "reasoning": "(a) **Time left until resolution**\nApproximately 96 days (from May 28, 2026 to September 1, 2026). This is a relatively short timeframe for major regulatory action.\n\n(b) **Status quo outcome if nothing changes**\nNo new formal restrictions are announced. While grid pressures continue to mount and some jurisdictions review policies, the administrative and political inertia required to pass binding new restrictions prevents formal action within this compressed timeframe. Existing informal restrictions (like EirGrid and TenneT's administrative measures) continue but are not formalized into new law.\n\n(c) **Scenario for NO outcome**\n- Continued grid pressure management through voluntary measures, queue management, and coordination rather than formal bans\n- Draft proposals or consultations are initiated but not finalized into binding rules before Sept 1\n- Individual grid operators take administrative action without formal government mandate (explicitly excluded from YES resolution)\n- Any new restrictions announced are reversed/rescinded before Sept 1\n- States/EU members choose to expand grid capacity rather than restrict data center connections\n\n(d) **Scenario for YES outcome**\n- At least one state (e.g., Virginia, Texas, or Georgia) or EU member state (e.g., Ireland, Netherlands, Denmark) formally announces a moratorium or binding restriction on new 50+ MW data center grid connections\n- The announcement occurs before September 1, 2026\n- It takes the form of enacted regulation, official policy directive, or formal written statement with force of law\n- It is not reversed before September 1, 2026\n- It represents a genuinely new restriction, not an extension of pre-existing measures\n\n(e) **Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?**\n\nLooking at historical precedent:\n- Ireland's EirGrid and Netherlands' TenneT imposed informal/administrative restrictions on data center connections over the past 2-3 years\n- Denmark announced a moratorium (referenced in the May 2026 CNBC article)\n- These represent administrative/informal actions, but formal legislative restrictions on large industrial infrastructure are rarer\n- In EU energy regulation, formal bans/moratoria on infrastructure categories occur perhaps once every 2-3 years across all EU member states combined\n- In the U.S., state-level formal restrictions on industrial infrastructure are even rarer \u2014 perhaps once every 3-5 years across all states combined\n- Base rate for ANY such restriction (EU + U.S. combined) in a 3-month period: approximately 15-25%\n\nHowever, the question specifies \"new\" restrictions in \"substantially the same form\" not pre-existing. This is critical: Denmark's May 2026 moratorium may already count as a recent action, reducing the likelihood of additional new announcements in the following 3 months.\n\n(f) **How current data/news moves me from base rate**\n\n**Factors pushing toward YES (increasing probability):**\n- Current date is May 28, 2026 \u2014 the background explicitly cites May 2026 CNBC article about Denmark's data center moratorium\n- Denmark's moratorium appears to already exist as of May 2026, suggesting the regulatory environment is actively moving toward restrictions\n- Ireland, Netherlands, and Denmark all have \"record length\" grid connection queues\n- Virginia, Texas, and Georgia are \"actively reviewing\" grid capacity allocation\n- The urgency of grid pressure is explicitly documented in recent EIA/DOE projections\n- The 96-day window captures the typical timeframe for regulatory announcement if political/technical groundwork is already done\n\n**Factors pushing toward NO (decreasing probability):**\n- The resolution requires \"new\" restrictions not in \"substantially the same form\" as pre-May 20 restrictions\n- Denmark's May 2026 moratorium may already constitute the \"new\" action that satisfies conditions, meaning additional announcements would be unusual\n- The timeframe is very short (96 days) for formal legislative/regulatory processes in the U.S. (requires public comment, legal review, etc.)\n- EU member states typically require 60-90 days minimum for formal consultation and enactment of binding rules\n- Most U.S. states require similar procedural timelines\n- Strong corporate lobbying and economic interest in data centers may slow formal action\n- Gridlock and institutional inertia favor status quo\n\n**Net adjustment from base rate:**\n- The Denmark moratorium already announced (May 2026) may have partially satisfied the resolution condition or made it already less likely another emerges in 3 months\n- However, if Denmark's action is being counted as \"already happened,\" then the question essentially asks: will ANY OTHER state announce something similar in the next 3 months?\n- The short timeframe and procedural requirements significantly constrain this likelihood despite high underlying pressure\n\n(g) **Community prediction divergence**\nI don't have access to stated community forecasts, but I can reason about likely disagreement:\n- If community forecasters heavily weight the imminent grid crisis and recent Denmark precedent, they may forecast 40-50%\n- I'm more conservative due to the procedural constraints of formal regulatory action and the 96-day timeframe\n- The distinction between \"administrative action by grid operators\" (which already happens) and \"binding government restriction\" (which is rarer) likely creates a divergence\n\n---\n\n**REASONING & PROBABILITY CALCULATION:**\n\n**Key analytical points:**\n\n1. **Denmark May 2026 moratorium**: The background cites a May 2026 CNBC article about Denmark's moratorium. This action appears to already be in effect as of May 28, 2026. The resolution criteria require a \"new restriction\" not in \"substantially the same form\" before May 20. If Denmark's moratorium was announced after May 20, 2026, it may already satisfy the condition, making YES resolution likely. If announced before May 20, it wouldn't count as \"new.\"\n\n2. **Procedural timeline constraint**: Even with political momentum, formal binding regulatory action requires:\n   - Legislative drafting or regulatory agency process initiation (1-2 weeks)\n   - Public comment period (minimum 30-45 days in most jurisdictions)\n   - Legal review and finalization (2-3 weeks)\n   - Announcement and enactment (1 week)\n   - Total: 50-75 days minimum\n   \n   This leaves only ~20 days for announcement in the compressed 96-day window if this question hasn't already been satisfied by Denmark.\n\n3. **Interpretation uncertainty**: The critical ambiguity is whether Denmark's May 2026 moratorium counts as a pre-existing restriction (before May 20) or as newly announced. The CNBC article is dated May 4, 2026, suggesting announcement well before May 20. If so, Denmark's action is ineligible as \"new,\" and the question asks whether ANY OTHER jurisdiction announces something between May 28 and Sept 1.\n\n4. **State-level U.S. likelihood (May 28-Sept 1)**: Virginia, Texas, and Georgia are \"actively reviewing\" but announcement of formal binding restrictions in 96 days is possible but not highly probable. These states typically require:\n   - Energy regulatory commission process (existing frameworks)\n   - Public hearings and comment\n   - Legislative approval in some cases\n   Probability: ~8-12% for at least one state in 96 days\n\n5. **EU member state likelihood (May 28-Sept 1)**: Ireland and Netherlands already took \"informal\" or \"administrative\" action (doesn't qualify). Other EU members (Poland, Germany, France) show less grid stress. If not Denmark or already-known jurisdictions, probability is lower. Probability: ~3-7% for a new EU member to announce in 96 days\n\n6. **Combined probability (assuming Denmark doesn't count as new)**:\n   - At least one U.S. state: 8-12%\n   - At least one EU member (non-Denmark): 3-7%\n   - Non-overlapping: ~10-18%\n\n7. **Adjustment for ambiguity**: If Denmark's May 4 moratorium DOES count as satisfying YES resolution, then YES should already be at ~100% because the condition is met. The fact that this question is still open suggests either:\n   - The moratorium doesn't count for technical reasons, OR\n   - We're still in the resolution window and it hasn't been officially confirmed yet\n   \n   This ambiguity itself suggests the true probability is somewhat muted.\n\n**Final synthesis:**\n\nGiven:\n- High underlying pressure (grid capacity crisis is real)\n- BUT short 96-day timeframe for formal action\n- AND procedural constraints in both U.S. and EU\n- AND possible threshold-already-met by Denmark (though unclear)\n- AND strong economic/lobbying counterweights\n- Calibration toward institutional conservatism and inertia\n\nI estimate the probability that a formal, binding new restriction is announced (and not rescinded)",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_38499": {
    "question_id": 38499,
    "question_text": "Will Escambia County athletes be more likely than non-athletes to have cross-race friendships in 2026?",
    "probability": 0.58,
    "reasoning": "Let me work through this systematically.\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nThe resolution date is June 30, 2026. Today is May 28, 2026. That's approximately 33 days remaining. The survey needs to be conducted by end of 2025-26 school year (typically mid-June), so we're in the final window for data collection.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nIf survey conduct proceeds as normal, we need to estimate what the actual difference would be between athletes and non-athletes having cross-race close friendships.\n\nCurrent base expectations:\n- Athletes likely have ~55-65% rate of cross-race friendships (due to sports' integrating nature)\n- Non-athletes likely have ~45-55% rate (reflecting broader school population patterns)\n- Expected difference: somewhere in the 5-15 percentage point range\n\nThe threshold is 5 percentage points, which is relatively modest.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- The actual survey shows athletes at 52% cross-race friendship rate and non-athletes at 50%, yielding only 2pp difference\n- Survey shows athletes at 58% and non-athletes at 56% (3pp difference)\n- Survey isn't conducted and question resolves AMBIGUOUS (though this seems unlikely given we're in late May)\n- Survey data is methodologically flawed and rejected\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- Survey shows athletes at 62% cross-race friendship rate vs non-athletes at 55% (7pp difference)\n- Survey shows athletes at 60% vs non-athletes at 50% (10pp difference)\n- The integrating effect of sports is empirically measurable at or above the 5pp threshold\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\nLooking at comparable research on sports and interracial contact:\n- Meta-analyses on sports and racial prejudice generally show effect sizes of 0.3-0.5 standard deviations\n- Studies on school extracurriculars and friendship segregation show meaningful but modest effects (typically 3-8 percentage point differences)\n- The Dick Appleyard/Ernest Dawson case represents a particularly strong example from an earlier era with more severe segregation\n- Modern research suggests integrating effects are real but often smaller than historical examples\n\nHistorical base rate for \"does activity X increase cross-group friendship by 5+ pp?\": roughly 40-50% in well-studied contexts with strong integration mechanisms.\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\nKey considerations:\n\n**Moving toward YES:**\n- The WUWF article provides very recent (2025) validation that sports integration still matters in Escambia specifically\n- Escambia County has 44.9% White, 34.3% Black, 9.8% Hispanic composition - relatively diverse, which facilitates cross-race friendships\n- The district explicitly offers 20+ sports across schools, suggesting robust athletic programs\n- Federal court orders (1973) and 1976 riots suggest the district has been actively managing racial integration for 50+ years\n- Sports are among the most effective school-based integration mechanisms studied\n\n**Moving toward NO:**\n- The 5pp threshold is relatively high for a survey-based measure with measurement error\n- Modern social circles may be more self-segregating than in Dick Appleyard's era despite integration\n- The survey asks about \"close friends\" which is a higher bar than acquaintances\n- School social patterns show persistent racial clustering even in integrated schools (documented in contemporary research)\n- Non-athletes in well-integrated schools may also have high cross-race friendship rates, compressing the difference\n\n**Neutral factors:**\n- We're only 33 days from resolution deadline, so survey timing risk exists but appears manageable\n- The 500-response minimum with 150 athletes/150 non-athletes is achievable for a school district survey\n\n## (g) Community prediction and divergence check\n\nI don't have access to current community forecaster consensus on this specific question. However, I should note: this is a relatively specialized local question about Escambia County specifically, so community forecasting data may be limited. \n\nIf community forecasters existed and were predicting the empirical survey outcome, I would expect them to center around 50-55% probability, given:\n- Reasonable theoretical basis for YES\n- But measurement/threshold challenges\n- Uncertainty about actual survey execution and results\n\nI'm not significantly diverging from what a well-calibrated forecast would suggest on this empirical question.\n\n## My Analysis\n\nThe core question is whether a survey will show a 5+ percentage point difference in cross-race friendship rates between athletes and non-athletes in Escambia County.\n\n**Theoretical support:** Strong. Sports do meaningfully increase interracial contact and friendship formation.\n\n**Empirical challenge:** The 5pp threshold is moderately high given:\n- Both groups (athletes and non-athletes) exist within the same integrated schools\n- Non-athletes in integrated schools also form cross-race friendships\n- Modern self-segregation patterns may be stronger than in the 1960s context\n\n**Measurement factors:**\n- Survey execution appears likely (we're in the final window)\n- The survey design is straightforward\n- Minimum sample sizes are achievable\n\n**Critical insight:** The question essentially asks whether the *marginal effect* of being an athlete is 5+ percentage points. If athletes are at 60% and non-athletes at 56%, that's only a 4pp effect and resolves NO. Even if the base rate of cross-race friendships is high (say 55% overall), the differential must be substantial.\n\nResearch on similar integrating activities suggests effect sizes of 3-8 percentage points are typical. The threshold of 5pp means we need to be above the median expected effect.\n\nGiven:\n- Theoretical support for YES (sports do integrate)\n- But the 5pp threshold requires a relatively strong effect\n- Uncertainty about actual survey results\n- Modern school contexts may show smaller differentials than historical cases\n\nI estimate the probability at **58%**.\n\nThis reflects:\n- Slight confidence that sports effects are real and measurable\n- But meaningful uncertainty about reaching the specific 5pp threshold\n- The threshold being set just above what research typically shows\n- Base rate for \"activity increases behavior by 5pp+\" being around 45-50%, adjusted upward slightly for sports' known integration power\n\n**Probability: 58%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
