    "reasoning": "# Analysis of Pope Leo XIV's International Travel (May 28 - September 1, 2026)\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nToday is May 28, 2026. The resolution date is September 1, 2026. That gives us approximately **96 days** until resolution.\n\nThe Spain visit runs June 6-12, 2026, leaving approximately **80 days** after the Spain trip for an additional country visit to occur.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nIf no new papal travels are announced, Pope Leo XIV will complete his Spain visit (June 6-12) and return to Rome. No other country visit would occur before September 1, 2026. This would resolve as **NO**.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- Pope Leo XIV completes only the scheduled Spain visit\n- No additional international travel is announced or executed before September 1, 2026\n- The Pope remains focused on Rome-based duties after the Spain trip\n- No unexpected crises or humanitarian events trigger an urgent papal visit\n- The 80-day window post-Spain is insufficient for another major pastoral trip to materialize\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- An international crisis, humanitarian emergency, or significant Church matter prompts an urgent papal visit to another country (e.g., natural disaster, conflict zone requiring papal presence, major interfaith dialogue)\n- Pope Leo XIV completes the Spain visit and announces another trip within the 80-day window\n- The trip occurs between June 13 and August 31, 2026\n- It is officially documented on the Vatican calendar\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\nLooking at Pope Leo XIV's established pattern:\n- **Since May 8, 2025 to May 28, 2026**: The Pope has visited 7 countries (Turkey, Lebanon, Monaco, Algeria, Cameroon, Angola, Equatorial Guinea) plus scheduled Spain = 8 countries in ~13 months\n- This suggests approximately **6-7 international trips per year** under Pope Leo XIV\n- With 80 days remaining (roughly 2.6 months), we'd expect **1.4-1.9 trips** based on current pace\n\nFor historical context on modern popes (Paul VI onwards):\n- International papal travel has become increasingly common\n- Popes often undertake 2-4 international trips per year\n- Unscheduled trips do occur in response to crises (~10-15% of annual trips are reactive/unscheduled)\n\n**Base rate: Approximately 40-50% probability** that a Pope traveling at this frequency would schedule another international trip within a 2.6-month window.\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves me from base rate\n\n**Factors pushing toward YES:**\n- Pope Leo XIV has demonstrated exceptionally high travel frequency (8 destinations in 13 months)\n- The 80-day post-Spain window is substantial enough for logistical planning\n- Geopolitical tensions remain (Middle East, conflicts in Africa, Eastern Europe) that could warrant papal intervention\n- Recent pattern shows no signs of slowing papal travel\n\n**Factors pushing toward NO:**\n- The Spain visit is a major undertaking (6 days of intensive engagement)\n- Late June/July/August are traditionally slower periods for papal travel (summer slowdown)\n- The Vatican typically schedules major trips well in advance; spontaneous trips are rarer\n- 80 days is actually quite compressed for planning a major international apostolic visit that isn't already announced\n- No international trips are currently visible on the Vatican calendar beyond Spain\n- The absence of pre-announcement (as of May 28) suggests none is imminent\n\n**Net adjustment: This moves me DOWN from the base rate.**\n\nThe critical factor is timing: we're already at May 28, and major papal trips are typically announced well in advance. The Spain visit wasn't mentioned in my background until after May 8, but it was formally scheduled on the Vatican calendar. No other June-August trips appear to be scheduled as of now. While the Pope's travel frequency is high, the lack of any announcement with only 80 days to go is notable.\n\n## (g) Community prediction comparison\nNo explicit community forecast data provided in the question. However, the Vatican's own scheduling practices suggest institutional momentum heavily favors pre-announced trips. The absence of a second trip announcement by late May, with the resolution window being June-August (traditionally slower months), indicates low institutional probability.\n\n---\n\n## Probability Estimate\n\nStarting from a base rate of ~45% given the Pope's exceptional travel frequency, I adjust downward significantly due to:\n1. Lack of pre-announcement (major negative signal)\n2. Timing clustering (Spain trip requires recovery/debriefing time)\n3. Summer slowdown patterns in Vatican scheduling\n4. Only 80 days remaining with no current indication\n\nHowever, I don't reduce too dramatically because:\n1. The Pope has shown genuine willingness to travel frequently\n2. Crisis-driven visits can be organized quickly\n3. The high travel pace suggests receptiveness to new trips\n\n**Probability: 28%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
