    "question_text": "Will the U.S. Senate pass another budget reconciliation bill before July 4, 2026?",
    "probability": 0.63,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis of Senate Reconciliation Bill Resolution\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nFrom May 28, 2026 to July 4, 2026 = **37 days** remaining\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nAs of the April 10 reporting, the Senate was actively working on a reconciliation bill with:\n- A June 1 deadline set by Trump\n- Leadership aiming to put a budget resolution on the floor by end of April\n- An active DHS shutdown creating political pressure\n- Republican control of the Senate with reconciliation as the primary tool to bypass the 60-vote threshold\n\nIf the current trajectory holds without major disruptions, passage by July 4 appears likely given the active push and stated timelines.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- **Internal GOP disagreement**: Senate Republicans fail to reach consensus on the reconciliation package scope (e.g., disagreement over ICE/CBP funding levels or unrelated provisions)\n- **Trump inconsistency**: Trump reverses his position or adds demands that fracture the coalition\n- **Procedural delays**: Budget resolution process encounters unexpected procedural obstacles or takes longer than anticipated\n- **Political shift**: A major news event or crisis diverts attention/political capital away from reconciliation\n- **Moderate defections**: Enough Republicans defect to prevent passage (though this is less likely in reconciliation context where only simple majority needed)\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- **Tight party unity**: Republican leaders successfully keep Trump aligned and maintain party discipline\n- **Timely process**: The budget resolution is completed on/near the end-of-April target, allowing for rapid floor votes\n- **Limited scope**: The bill stays focused on DHS funding (ICE/CBP) for 3 years as outlined, avoiding provisions that create internal dissent\n- **Execution**: Senate moves the bill through in May, well ahead of the July 4 deadline\n- **37 days remaining** provides substantial buffer beyond the June 1 Trump deadline\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n- **Reconciliation bills in general**: Congress passes 0-2 reconciliation bills per Congress (biennial). When leadership attempts them, they succeed roughly 60-70% of the time\n- **Senate party-line reconciliation with unified control**: When one party controls the chamber and has leadership consensus, success rate is very high (~75-85%)\n- **Timeline compression**: Passing major legislation in 37 days is feasible but moderately challenging; historically some reconciliation efforts take 2-3 months\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Positive indicators moving toward YES:**\n- Active leadership engagement (Graham, Barrasso meeting with Trump on April 10)\n- Clear political urgency (DHS shutdown creating pressure)\n- Announced end-of-April timeline for budget resolution gives 5+ weeks for floor action\n- Trump set June 1 deadline, showing commitment\n- Only needs simple majority (no filibuster risk)\n- **Critically: We're already at May 28 with 37 days left** \u2014 if the April timeline was met, the bill should be moving through the chamber now or very soon\n\n**Negative indicators moving toward NO:**\n- \"Incredibly tricky attempt\" language suggests significant negotiating challenges\n- Trump's \"hot and cold\" behavior creates unpredictability\n- Risk of bill ballooning beyond original scope\n- No evidence from current news that the end-of-April budget resolution deadline was actually met (this would be a red flag)\n\n**Information gap**: The prompt provides data through April 10-11, but we're now at May 28. The absence of news reporting that the budget resolution passed or is imminent in late May is somewhat concerning. If leaders had stuck to the end-of-April timeline, we should see clear signals of floor consideration in mid-May.\n\n## (g) Community prediction comparison\nNo explicit community forecast is provided in the prompt, so I cannot assess divergence. However, my reasoning:\n- Base rates for party-line reconciliation with unified control: 75-85%\n- Timeline feasibility with 37 days: +5-10% (more than enough time)\n- Trump unpredictability and coalition management challenges: -10-15%\n- Unknown status as of May 28 on whether April timeline was met: -5-10%\n\n## Probability Calculation\n\n**Starting base rate for Senate reconciliation passage when party controls chamber and leadership supports**: 75%\n\n**Adjustments:**\n- Timeline is tight but feasible (37 days is adequate for already-drafted reconciliation): +5%\n- Some evidence of organized push and Trump involvement: +3%\n- Trump's inconsistency and \"tricky\" language from sources: -8%\n- Lack of clear news about April 10-end of April progress (concerning signal): -10%\n- DHS shutdown creates genuine pressure to pass: +3%\n\n**Adjusted estimate: 75 + 5 + 3 - 8 - 10 + 3 = 68%**\n\nHowever, the fact that we're now at May 28 with no reported passage yet is moderately concerning relative to the end-of-April timeline originally discussed. This suggests some slippage. Applying additional -5% for this timeline concern:\n\n**Final estimate: 63%**\n\nThis reflects:\n- Strong base rate for party-line reconciliation\n- Adequate time remaining (37 days)\n- But some concerning delays relative to original timeline\n- Real uncertainty around Trump's continued support\n- Moderate but not overwhelming confidence\n\n**Probability: 63%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_40928": {
    "question_id": 40928,
    "question_text": "Will Bitcoin reach a new all-time high price before October 6, 2026?",
    "probability": 0.22,
    "reasoning": "I'll work through this systematically.\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nFrom May 28, 2026 to October 6, 2026: approximately **131 days** (about 4.3 months)\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nBitcoin is currently at $72,958, down 3.7% over the past month and well below the ATH of $126,198 set on October 6, 2025. If price action continues at historical volatility without a major catalyst, Bitcoin would likely remain in its current range or trend lower given recent momentum. Status quo suggests NO.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- Bitcoin continues its recent downward trend or consolidates sideways\n- Macro headwinds (rising rates, geopolitical tension, recession concerns) persist\n- Regulatory crackdowns or negative news dampens institutional interest\n- The 4-month timeframe proves insufficient for a ~73% rally from current levels\n- This is the baseline expectation given current price action and momentum\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- Major positive macro catalyst (Fed pivot, inflation collapse, geopolitical resolution)\n- Broad risk-on environment returning liquidity to crypto assets\n- Institutional adoption accelerates (corporate treasury moves, pension fund entry)\n- Bitcoin ETF inflows surge dramatically\n- Narrative shift toward inflation hedge gains traction\n- A sustained bull run over the next 4 months drives price above $126,198\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\nLooking at Bitcoin's historical patterns:\n- Bitcoin has set new ATHs roughly every 2-4 years during bull markets\n- Following previous ATH peaks (2017, 2021), Bitcoin took 3-4 years to exceed them during subsequent bull markets\n- Within a 4-month window: Bitcoin has occasionally made explosive moves, but surpassing a previous ATH this quickly is relatively rare\n- The October 2025 ATH was just set ~7 months ago; breaking it within 9 months from that peak would be faster than historical norms\n- Historical base rate for \"new ATH within 4-5 months after already hitting ATH\" is approximately 15-25%\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves me from base rate\n\n**Bearish adjustments:**\n- Current price of $72,958 is 42% below the ATH \u2014 requires a substantial $53,000+ rally\n- 30-day change is negative (-3.7%), suggesting momentum is downward\n- We're already 7+ months into a potential bull cycle (if one began at the Oct 2025 ATH); bull markets typically show sustained strength early, not weakness\n- Forbes warning of potential 3-trillion crypto collapse and $10k Bitcoin predictions indicate significant bearish sentiment exists\n- Bitcoin trading below $100k for the past 6+ months suggests consolidation/distribution rather than accumulation\n\n**Bullish adjustments:**\n- Bitwise, Standard Chartered, and Bernstein specifically predict a new ATH in 2026 (which includes the remaining 4+ months)\n- We have ~4.3 months remaining \u2014 enough time for a volatility event if macro conditions shift\n- Institutional adoption continues growing despite price weakness (ETFs, corporate holdings)\n- Bitcoin halving cycle dynamics could still support price (historically halvings precede bull runs, though with lag)\n- A 73% move, while large, is not unprecedented for crypto in short timeframes\n\n**Net adjustment:** The bearish signals are stronger than bullish ones at present. The recent price weakness, the magnitude of rally required (73%), and the short timeframe all suggest this is below the base rate. I'm adjusting downward from the 15-25% base rate.\n\n## (g) Community prediction vs my estimate\n\nThe mentioned forecasts (Bitwise, Standard Chartered, Bernstein) predict a new ATH \"in 2026\" generally, not specifically before October 6. This is meaningful \u2014 they may be forecasting an ATH later in 2026 (Q4) rather than by early October. This distinction matters significantly for a probability assessment.\n\nThe Forbes warning of collapse suggests substantial disagreement in the forecasting community, indicating high uncertainty.\n\n---\n\n## My Reasoning:\n\n**Key considerations:**\n1. The current price requires a 73% gain in 131 days\n2. Historical volatility in crypto can support this, but momentum is currently negative\n3. Remaining time is non-trivial (4+ months) but not generous\n4. Most analyst forecasts for \"2026 ATH\" likely envision later in the year\n5. The market has shown weakness since hitting the ATH in October 2025\n6. Major macro catalyst would be needed to reverse current momentum\n\n**Calibration check:** \n- At 25%: I'd be saying Bitcoin has a 1-in-4 chance of a 73% rally in 4 months with current negative momentum \u2014 seems slightly generous\n- At 20%: This reflects \"possible but unlikely given current conditions, negative momentum, and short timeframe\"\n- At 15%: This would be more pessimistic than historical base rates warrant\n\nGiven the negative price momentum, the requirement for a substantial move, the short timeframe remaining, but acknowledging the possibility of a macro catalyst and that institutional adoption continues, I'll weight this toward the lower end of plausible range.\n\n**Probability: 22%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_41425": {
    "question_id": 41425,
    "question_text": "Will the 2026 U.S. midterm elections be considered \"free and fair\"?",
    "probability": 0.82,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis of 2026 U.S. Midterm Election \"Free and Fair\" Resolution\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\n\nThe question resolves on January 20, 2027. Today is May 28, 2026. This means we have approximately **7.5 months** until resolution. The 2026 midterm elections will occur on November 3, 2026, leaving roughly 2.5 months after the election for certification, audits, investigations, and official assessments.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\n\nIf current trends continue without major disruptions:\n- Elections proceed as administered in recent cycles\n- Results are certified by states following established procedures\n- Post-election audits occur as scheduled in various jurisdictions\n- International observers (OSCE, Carter Center) conduct assessments\n- EAC monitors compliance with federal standards\n- Absent widespread fraud findings, results stand\n- The baseline outcome is election certification and acceptance, though with continued partisan disagreement about specific safeguards\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n\nFor resolution as NO, we would need evidence of one or more of:\n- **Widespread fraud/irregularities**: Court rulings or official investigations finding outcome-determinative fraud across multiple states (not isolated instances)\n- **Systemic disenfranchisement**: EAC, OSCE, or Carter Center concluding basic democratic standards were violated through widespread voter suppression, intimidation, or manipulation\n- **Certification failure**: Results not certified by state authorities, or Congress rejecting certified results due to documented systemic problems\n- **Outcome determinative suppression**: Court findings of voter suppression so extensive it affected electoral outcomes across jurisdictions\n\nThe key word is \"widespread\" and \"outcome-determinative\" \u2014 isolated problems don't trigger NO resolution.\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n\nFor resolution as YES, we need:\n- States certify election results through normal procedures\n- Congress accepts results in accordance with federal law\n- No widespread invalidation occurs due to fraud or systemic irregularities\n- EAC, OSCE, and Carter Center don't conclude elections failed basic democratic standards due to widespread disenfranchisement, intimidation, or manipulation\n- Courts don't find widespread, outcome-determinative voter suppression/fraud/intimidation across multiple states\n- Isolated problems or areas for improvement are acceptable for YES resolution\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\n**U.S. midterm elections being certified \"free and fair\":**\n\n- **Since 1980** (11 midterm cycles): All have been certified and results accepted by Congress without systematic evidence of outcome-determinative fraud\n- **2022 midterms**: Certified, accepted, observed as having normal procedural safeguards despite partisan claims\n- **2018 midterms**: Certified and accepted with standard post-election processes\n- **2014, 2010, 2006**: All certified without widespread fraud findings\n- **2002, 1998, 1994, 1990, 1986, 1982, 1980**: All certified\n- **Historical rate**: 100% of recent U.S. midterms have met the basic certification and acceptance criteria outlined in the resolution criteria\n\n**International observer assessments:**\n- U.S. elections since 2000 have consistently been assessed by OSCE and other observers as meeting basic democratic standards, though with notes on areas for improvement\n- No recent U.S. midterm has been declared to have failed basic democratic standards by OSCE or Carter Center\n\n**Base rate for \"free and fair\" designation**: Approximately **95-98%** based on modern U.S. electoral history.\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Factors supporting YES (towards the 95%+ base rate):**\n\n1. **Institutional resilience**: Despite post-2020 political polarization, the 2022 midterms proceeded with normal administration and certification\n2. **Decentralized system**: Multiple competing jurisdictions and state-level authority creates redundancy; widespread fraud would need coordination across states with different administrations\n3. **Established procedures**: Well-developed election administration, audit procedures, and legal frameworks are in place\n4. **Time remaining**: 7.5 months is sufficient for proper election administration, though tight for major corrective actions\n5. **2022 precedent**: Recent election proceeded smoothly despite elevated polarization\n6. **No current crisis**: As of May 2026, no widespread election administration crisis has emerged\n\n**Factors supporting NO (away from base rate):**\n\n1. **Ongoing partisan polarization**: Trust in elections remains divided along party lines; some will dispute results regardless\n2. **Election administration pressures**: Staffing shortages, funding constraints in some jurisdictions persist\n3. **Increased litigation risk**: Pattern of post-election legal challenges has increased since 2020\n4. **Voter ID and access disputes**: Ongoing controversies over voter ID requirements, ballot access, and redistricting create friction\n5. **Misinformation environment**: Social media and partisan media may amplify unfounded fraud claims\n6. **State election law changes**: Some states have enacted new voting restrictions or procedures that could create implementation challenges\n\n**Net assessment of current data movement:**\nThe current environment shows slightly elevated risk compared to the 2000-2020 baseline, but nothing approaching the threshold for \"widespread\" fraud or systemic failure. The 2022 midterms occurred successfully under similar conditions. I estimate current conditions support a probability slightly **below** the historical base rate due to elevated polarization and litigation risk, but well above 50%.\n\n## (g) Community prediction and divergence\n\nI do not have access to current community forecasting data on this specific question as of May 28, 2026. However, based on typical forecaster behavior:\n\n- **Expected community estimate**: Likely 70-85% (acknowledging both the strong base rate and elevated post-2020 partisan polarization)\n- **My estimate vs. community**: I would likely be at the lower end of that range or slightly below if the community is at 75%+\n\n**Why I might diverge:**\n- I weight the strong 20+ year track record of successful certification heavily\n- I'm cautious about overweighting recent polarization beyond what 2022 demonstrated could be managed\n- I apply skepticism to \"widespread\" fraud claims given their consistent rejection in courts since 2020\n- I note that the resolution criteria explicitly allow isolated problems, raising the threshold for NO\n- However, I also weight elevated litigation risk and polarization more than pure historical base rates would suggest\n\n## Final Probability Assessment\n\n**Key anchoring factors:**\n- Base rate: ~95% of recent U.S. midterms certified successfully\n- 2022 recent precedent under similar polarization: YES outcome\n- Resolution criteria require \"widespread,\" \"outcome-determinative\" problems (high bar)\n- Time remaining for normal election administration: 7.5 months (adequate)\n- Institutional factors: Decentralized system, established procedures, legal frameworks\n\n**Adjustment factors:**\n- Elevated polarization since 2020: -5 to -8 percentage points\n- Increased litigation risk and election administration challenges: -2 to -3 percentage points\n- Misinformation environment: Already partially captured in base rate\n- Balanced by resolution criteria explicitly allowing isolated problems: +2 percentage points\n\n**Calculation:**\nStarting at 95% base rate \u2192 subtract 5-8% for elevated polarization \u2192 subtract 2-3% for administration/legal risk \u2192 add back ~2% for flexible resolution criteria = **82-87%**\n\nAccounting for remaining uncertainty and the fact that 7.5 months is relatively short for major corrective interventions if problems emerge, I settle toward the middle-lower end of this range.\n\n**Probability: 82%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_42575": {
    "question_id": 42575,
    "question_text": "Will Iran participate in the 2026 FIFA World Cup?",
    "probability": 0.06,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis of Iran's 2026 FIFA World Cup Participation\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nThe 2026 FIFA World Cup begins in June 2026 (approximately 2-3 weeks from today, May 28, 2026). Group matches begin almost immediately, meaning there is very limited time for the situation to resolve. The tournament's start is imminent.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nIf nothing changes from the current trajectory, Iran would not participate. As of March 12, 2026:\n- Iran's sports minister declared unambiguous non-participation\n- Trump stated Iran should not participate \"for their own safety\"\n- Major combat operations between US and Iran are ongoing (with Supreme Leader Khamenei reportedly killed)\n- No formal FIFA decision has been made, but the organization is \"monitoring\"\n- There has been approximately 2.5 months of escalation and no reversal of Iran's stated position\n\nThe status quo clearly points to non-participation.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- Iran maintains its stated refusal to participate due to the military conflict and assassination of its supreme leader\n- FIFA does not compel Iran's participation (they cannot suspend a nation for non-participation in a qualifier they've won)\n- Iran's government views participation as incompatible with national dignity and ongoing conflict\n- A substitute nation (likely Iraq, based on reporting about playoff scenarios) takes Iran's spot, or the spot remains unfilled\n- This is the most probable scenario given current facts\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- Dramatic de-escalation or ceasefire agreement between US and Iran in the next 2-3 weeks\n- Iran's government reverses its position and decides participation serves national interests better than boycott\n- New Iranian leadership (post-Khamenei succession) takes a different stance on participation\n- FIFA enforces participation requirements (highly unlikely given precedent)\n- This would require a fundamental shift in Iran's calculus within an extremely compressed timeframe\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\nHistorical precedent for nations withdrawing from World Cups due to conflict:\n- **1980 Moscow Olympics**: 65+ nations boycotted due to Soviet invasion of Afghanistan\n- **2022 World Cup**: Russia was banned/excluded due to invasion of Ukraine (not a withdrawal)\n- **1950s onward**: Multiple nations have withdrawn due to civil conflict, political crises\n- **General pattern**: When a nation's government declares non-participation due to existential conflict with the host nation, they virtually never reverse this decision in the immediate term\n- **Historical base rate for boycott reversal within 2-3 weeks**: Less than 5%\n\nThe precedent suggests once a government takes a strong public position opposing participation due to armed conflict with the host nation, reversals are extraordinarily rare in such compressed timeframes.\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Factors pushing toward NO (strengthening the base rate):**\n- The situation is not hypothetical\u2014there is active armed conflict\n- The Iranian sports minister's statement was unambiguous and official\n- Trump explicitly warned against participation \"for safety\"\n- Supreme Leader Khamenei was reportedly killed in combat operations\n- Only 2-3 weeks remain\u2014insufficient time for meaningful de-escalation\n- Iran has already qualified; they are not motivated by access\n- No recent reporting suggests any move toward reversal\n- The conflict appears to be escalating, not de-escalating\n\n**Factors pushing toward YES (weakening the base rate):**\n- FIFA's stated position is to \"monitor\" rather than enforce Iranian exclusion\n- Trump's statement about Iran being \"welcome\" (March 11) provides diplomatic cover if Iran reverses\n- Prestigious sporting participation can sometimes be leveraged in ceasefire negotiations (though unlikely in 2-3 weeks)\n- Historical instances of last-minute reversals (very rare but exist)\n\nThe current data overwhelmingly reinforces the base rate of non-participation.\n\n## (g) Community prediction and divergence\nNo specific community forecast is provided in the prompt. However, this question would likely be polarized:\n- Some forecasters might overweight diplomatic rhetoric and FIFA's \"open door\" stance\n- Others might underweight the severity of the military conflict and Iran's explicit refusal\n- The imminent resolution date should concentrate forecasts toward the extremes (very low or very high)\n\nMy analysis suggests the correct divergence is toward very low probability, as the base rate of boycott reversal in active conflict situations is low, and the timeframe is compressed.\n\n---\n\n## Reasoning Summary\n\nThe critical facts:\n1. Iran's government has made an explicit, unambiguous statement of non-participation\n2. This was made in context of active military conflict with the host nation\n3. The Supreme Leader was reportedly killed in this conflict\n4. Only 2-3 weeks remain until the tournament\n5. Historical precedent shows such boycotts are not reversed quickly\n6. Current news shows no movement toward de-escalation or Iranian reversal\n7. Iran has already qualified and faces no threat of access denial\n\nThe scenario for YES requires one of: dramatic ceasefire, new Iranian leadership reversing course immediately, or FIFA forcing participation (impossible). None are plausible in 2-3 weeks given active hostilities.\n\nThe scenario for NO aligns with current trajectory, stated government position, historical precedent, and the compressed timeframe.\n\n**Probability: 6%**\n\nThis accounts for: minimal base rate probability of last-minute reversal (~3-5%), plus a small contingency for unexpected diplomatic breakthroughs or misinterpretation of current reports (~1-2%), while recognizing that the overwhelming evidence points to non-participation.",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_43432": {
    "question_id": 43432,
    "question_text": "Will there be a successful coup in Africa or Latin America before September 1, 2026?",
    "probability": 0.18,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis: Successful Coup in Africa or Latin America Before September 1, 2026\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nApproximately **95 days** (from May 28, 2026 to September 1, 2026)\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nGiven current political stability trajectories, no successful coup occurs. Most countries maintain their existing power structures. A ~3-month window is relatively short for major political upheavals to develop and execute.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- Political tensions in unstable countries (Mali, Burkina Faso, parts of Central America) simmer but don't boil over into successful coups\n- Any coup attempts are suppressed by loyal forces\n- Constitutional crises or elections proceed through legal/semi-legal channels rather than military seizure\n- Incumbent leaders consolidate power through institutional means rather than coups\n- International pressure and regional organizations (AU, OAS) continue to deter military takeovers\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- A military faction in an unstable West African country (Mali, Burkina Faso, Guinea) successfully executes a coup, rapidly securing military and government control\n- Alternatively, an incumbent leader in a politically volatile nation (Venezuela, Bolivia, Peru, or Central America) attempts a self-coup/refuses to relinquish power after elections/constitutional term limits, successfully consolidating control\n- A rapid, coordinated strike by military or elites overwhelms institutional resistance before international intervention\n- The coup establishes effective control within days/weeks, meeting the \"successful\" criteria\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\n**Africa (last 5 years of data presented):**\n- Guinea-Bisau (Nov 2025), Madagascar (Oct 2025), Mali (2020-2021), Niger (2023), Gabon (2023), Burkina Faso (2022 x2), Guinea (2021) \n- Approximately 8+ successful coups in Africa from 2020-2025 (5-year period) = ~1.6 per year\n- Africa has ~54 countries, so roughly 3% of African countries experience successful coups per year\n- Over a 3-month window: ~0.75% of African countries, or ~0.4 countries expected\n\n**Latin America (same period):**\n- Peru self-coup attempt (2022), Brazil Congress attack (2023), Bolivia coup attempt (2024)\n- Notably: these are mostly **unsuccessful** or borderline cases\n- Only 0 clearly successful coups in Latin America 2020-2025, with 3-4 attempts\n- Much lower coup success rate than Africa\n- Over 35 countries in Latin America, far more institutionally robust democracies overall\n\n**Combined regional base rate:**\n- ~8-9 successful coups across ~89 countries in 5 years = ~1.8% annual probability for any given country\n- With ~89 countries at risk, expected coups per year \u2248 1.6\n- Over 3 months \u2248 0.4 coups expected\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves me from base rate\n\n**Factors increasing probability:**\n1. **Recent acceleration in Africa**: Two coups in last 6 months (Guinea-Bisau Nov 2025, Madagascar Oct 2025) suggest elevated instability\n2. **West African hotspot**: Mali, Burkina Faso, Niger have shown repeated coup activity; these remain volatile\n3. **Ongoing conflicts**: Sahel insurgencies create opportunities for military takeover under guise of security concerns\n4. **Self-coup precedent**: Peru's 2022 self-coup attempt shows Latin American leaders willing to attempt power consolidation outside democratic norms\n5. **Election cycles**: Some Latin American countries may have elections in mid-2026 where incumbent leaders resist term limits\n\n**Factors decreasing probability:**\n1. **Recent successful coups reduce near-term risk**: Countries that just experienced coups (Guinea-Bisau, Madagascar) have new military governments; less likelihood of immediate follow-up coups\n2. **3-month window is short**: Organizing a successful coup typically requires months of preparation\n3. **International monitoring**: AU, ECOWAS, OAS now closely monitor coup risks and apply sanctions; deterrent effect\n4. **Latin America's institutional strength**: Much more stable than Africa; attempted coups (Bolivia 2024, Brazil 2023) have failed\n5. **Regional military coordination**: ECOWAS and other bodies have resources to suppress coups in vulnerable regions\n\n**Net adjustment**: The recent acceleration in African coups partially counterbalances the short timeframe and increased international vigilance. However, the 3-month window is still quite restrictive for new coup organization.\n\n## (g) Community prediction comparison\n\nI don't have access to current community predictions on this specific question. If a community forecast exists significantly above or below my estimate, I would consider:\n- Whether they're extrapolating the recent coup acceleration more aggressively\n- Whether they're weighting African vs Latin American risks differently\n- Whether they have more current intelligence on specific countries (Venezuela, Mali, Burkina Faso)\n\n---\n\n## Probability Calculation\n\n**Base rate over 3 months**: ~0.4 coups expected across both regions, with most risk concentrated in West Africa (Mali, Burkina Faso, Guinea, Niger). This translates to roughly **15-20%** probability of at least one successful coup in the 95-day window.\n\n**Adjustments:**\n- Recent coup clustering (Guinea-Bisau, Madagascar) suggests elevated but not dramatically elevated risk: **+3-5%**\n- Short 3-month timeframe and international monitoring: **-5-7%**\n- Latin America's low coup risk: **-2-3%** (already reflected in base rate)\n- Self-coup risk in Peru/Venezuela if elections occur: **+1-2%**\n\n**Final estimate**: Starting from 17% base rate for 3-month window, adjusting for recent data and current conditions.\n\nThe most likely scenario for a YES resolution involves West African military intervention (Mali, Burkina Faso, or Guinea-Conakry), though even with elevated regional instability, a 95-day window remains relatively short for coup organization and execution.\n\n**Probability: 18%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_43307": {
    "question_id": 43307,
    "question_text": "Will there be a nationwide anti-government uprising in Russia between September 20 and November 1, 2026?",
    "probability": 0.03,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis of Nationwide Anti-Government Uprising in Russia (Sept 20 - Nov 1, 2026)\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nApproximately 4 months until September 20, 2026, and 5 months until the end of the resolution window (November 1, 2026).\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nIf economic and political conditions remain as they are in late May 2026, Russia would likely hold its scheduled September 2026 State Duma elections with routine management of dissent through existing state apparatus. Isolated protests might occur, but they would remain localized, uncoordinated, and manageable through conventional security measures. The Kremlin has successfully suppressed larger movements in the past (2011-2013, 2019-2021) while maintaining administrative control.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- Economic conditions stabilize or improve before September\n- The Kremlin effectively co-opts or marginalizes key figures like Bonya and other dissidents\n- Protests remain geographically fragmented (concentrated in major cities but not spreading nationally)\n- Unrest stays below the violence threshold or remains non-confrontational\n- Security forces maintain control without large-scale federal deployment\n- The Kremlin avoids public acknowledgment of extraordinary threats\n- International media coverage remains below the threshold of three major outlets specifically labeling events as \"uprising/revolutionary unrest\"\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- Economic deterioration accelerates beyond current 1.8% contraction trajectory\n- Widespread public mobilization coalesces around anti-war sentiment, economic grievances, or electoral manipulation\n- Mass protests occur simultaneously in Moscow, St. Petersburg, and at least 3 other federal subjects (e.g., Novosibirsk, Yekaterinburg, Vladivostok, Krasnoyarsk)\n- Confrontations escalate to violence, rioting, or seizures of administrative buildings\n- The Kremlin responds with National Guard/military deployment at scale\n- Major international news organizations characterize events as \"uprising\" or \"revolutionary unrest\"\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 How often do similar events occur?\n\n**Russian historical precedent:**\n- 1917 Revolution: 1 (109 years ago)\n- Major nationwide anti-government uprisings in modern Russia: 0 since 1991\n- Large-scale protests suppressed by security forces: 2011-2013 (Bolotnaya Square), 2019-2021 (Navalny protests) \u2014 but neither was nationwide or met YES criteria\n- Countries with anti-government uprisings in 2015-2025: Approximately 10-15 globally (Syria, Sudan, Hong Kong, Myanmar, Iran, Belarus partially, etc.)\n\n**Global frequency:** In any given year, there are typically 3-5 cases of major anti-government uprisings globally that meet stringent criteria (multi-city, violent, security response). Russia has not experienced one since 1991 across 35 years.\n\n**Adjusted base rate for Russia:** ~1-3% annually for a nationwide uprising meeting all three criteria.\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Factors pushing toward YES:**\n1. **Economic deterioration:** The reported 1.8% contraction in early 2026 is significant. This is a material economic shock that historically can trigger unrest.\n2. **Elite criticism breaking surface:** Bonya's viral video and Zyuganov's warning suggest cracks in the consensus facade that the Kremlin typically maintains.\n3. **Multiple pressure vectors:** War fatigue, economic weakness, and administrative failures (disasters, agricultural problems) create compounding grievances.\n4. **Timing with elections:** September 2026 elections create a focal point for political expression.\n5. **Rare coordination hints:** References to dissent from pro-Kremlin figures suggest unusual alignment of grievances.\n\n**Factors pushing toward NO:**\n1. **Kremlin's proven capacity:** Russia has successfully suppressed movements in 2011-2013 and 2019-2021 that were large but failed to become nationwide, violent uprisings meeting all criteria.\n2. **Institutional control:** The state apparatus (FSB, National Guard, local security) is highly professionalized at suppression.\n3. **Fragmentation of opposition:** Despite Bonya's video and Zyuganov's warning, there's no indication of coordinated leadership or organizational capacity.\n4. **Internet control:** Russia has substantial ability to limit coordination of mass movements.\n5. **Economic contraction is not catastrophic:** A 1.8% contraction is serious but not 2008 financial crisis-level (which didn't cause uprisings in Russia either).\n6. **Historical baseline is very low:** Russia hasn't had a nationwide uprising in 35 years despite multiple economic and political crises.\n7. **Time horizon is short:** 4 months is relatively brief for a political crisis to escalate to this scale from current baseline.\n8. **Election timing cuts both ways:** While it creates a focal point, the Kremlin can use controlled elections to release pressure.\n\n**Specificity of criteria matters:**\nThe YES condition requires ALL THREE of:\n- At least three major outlets calling it an \"uprising\"\n- Violent protests in Moscow/St. Petersburg PLUS at least 3 other federal subjects\n- Either state of emergency, large-scale military deployment, OR public acknowledgment of extraordinary threat\n\nThis is a high bar. Even significant unrest (like 2019-2021) might not trigger all three.\n\n## (g) Community prediction alignment\n\nI don't have access to current community predictions on this specific question. However, I would expect:\n- Superforecasters to be skeptical (~15-25%) given Russia's proven suppression capacity\n- Some analysts focused on Russian fragility to be more bullish (~30-40%) given economic signals\n- Base rate thinkers to anchor around 3-5% (historical frequency)\n\nMy estimate would likely align with the skeptical end but slightly higher than pure base rate due to the clustering of warning signs in the background brief.\n\n---\n\n## Probability Calculation\n\n**Anchoring on base rate:** ~2% for similar events in Russia annually\n\n**Adjustments upward:**\n- Economic contraction provides material trigger: +1-2%\n- Elite dissent breaking surface (unusual): +0.5-1%\n- Multiple simultaneous grievances: +0.5%\n- 5-month window (longer than one year base rate): base rate is already for ~12 months; this is 5 months, so scale down slightly\n\n**Adjustments downward:**\n- Kremlin's proven suppression capacity: -0.5%\n- Short timeframe (crisis escalation takes time): -1%\n- Very specific YES criteria (all three must occur): -1.5%\n- No visible coordinated opposition leadership: -1%\n- Internet control limiting coordination: -0.5%\n\n**Intermediate estimate:** 2% \u00d7 (1.4x upward) / (1.2x downward) \u2248 2.3%\n\n**Reality check:**\n- This feels roughly right: unlikely but non-trivial given warning signs\n- Not confident enough to go below 2% (ignoring the economic data)\n- Not bullish enough to exceed 5% (institutional control too strong, timescale too short)\n- The clustering of warning signs (Bonya, Zyuganov, economic contraction) is notably worse than baseline but doesn't overcome the structural barriers\n\n**Final estimate:** 3-4% range\n\nGiven the specificity of the YES criteria (requiring all three conditions), the short timeframe, and Russia's historical track record of suppression, I'll settle at the lower end of this range.\n\n---\n\n**Probability: 3%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_43507": {
