  },
  "q_40795": {
    "question_id": 40795,
    "question_text": "Will the winner of the 2026 FIFA World Cup be a country that has never won before?",
    "probability": 0.06,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis of 2026 FIFA World Cup Winner Question\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nApproximately 2 weeks (tournament runs June 11 - July 19, 2026). The tournament is imminent.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nOne of the 8 traditional powerhouses wins (Uruguay, Italy, Germany, Brazil, England, Argentina, France, or Spain). This has been the case for all 21 previous World Cups since 1930 (excluding war years).\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\nOne of the established eight powerhouses wins the tournament. This would be:\n- Brazil (most successful historically, last won 2002)\n- France (reigning champion from 2022, strong team)\n- Argentina (recently dominant, won 2022)\n- Germany (4-time champion, consistently competitive)\n- England (improving, reached Euro 2020 final)\n- Spain (won 2010, still strong)\n- Italy (champions but missed 2022 World Cup)\n- Uruguay (historic champion but less competitive recently)\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\nA historically non-winning nation claims the title. Candidates include:\n- Netherlands (3-time finalists, very strong team)\n- Belgium (strong squad, consistent performer)\n- Portugal (competitive in recent tournaments)\n- Denmark, Mexico, USA (host advantage for USA/Mexico)\n- Other dark horses (Netherlands seems most plausible)\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\n**Historical precedent is extremely strong:**\n- 21 World Cups have been held\n- 8 different countries have won\n- 0 \"new winner\" outcomes in 94 years of competition\n- Base rate = 0/21 = **0%**\n\nThis is the most entrenched pattern in international football. The same 8 nations have maintained dominance across nearly a century, despite ~200 FIFA-registered nations competing.\n\n**However, base rates should be tempered by:**\n- Historical patterns can break (they eventually do)\n- Netherlands has been to 3 finals but never won\n- Parity has increased in recent decades (more competitive nations)\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Factors pushing toward NO (maintaining tradition):**\n- France is defending champion with experienced squad\n- Argentina just won 2022 with cohesive team and momentum\n- Brazil has strengthened and is historically dominant\n- England and Germany remain perennial contenders\n- The eight nations have deep institutional advantages (infrastructure, training systems, talent development)\n\n**Factors pushing toward YES (enabling new winner):**\n- Netherlands' tournament track record (3 finals, quality squad)\n- Belgium has developed a genuinely competitive team\n- USA/Mexico host advantage (hosts have won multiple times historically)\n- Broader globalization of football quality has improved non-traditional nations\n- Portugal, Denmark are competitive in modern football\n\n**Critical consideration:** Even with increased parity, the 8 traditional winners have won EVERY SINGLE World Cup. Breaking a 94-year pattern is extraordinarily rare, even if probability has slightly increased.\n\n## (g) Community prediction comparison\n\nI don't have access to current betting markets or community forecasts, but typical odds likely reflect:\n- Strong favorites among the 8 (France, Argentina, Brazil typically favored)\n- Netherlands as highest-probability \"new winner\" at maybe 2-5%\n- Other non-traditional nations at <1% each\n\nMy estimate should be in that ballpark or slightly higher given the genuinely increased competitiveness of football globally.\n\n## Probability Reasoning:\n\nStarting from the 0% historical base rate:\n- **Add ~3-5% for genuine increase in parity** in modern football\n- **Add ~1-2% for Netherlands' persistent quality** despite never winning\n- **Subtract caution** for how entrenched the 8-nation dominance is\n- **Anchor heavily on historical record** - 0/21 is staggering persistence\n\nThe fact that this pattern has held for 94 years across massive geopolitical, economic, and sporting changes is evidence of deep structural advantages these 8 nations possess.\n\nHowever, it's not impossible. Netherlands, Belgium, or even a dark horse like Portugal/Denmark have non-trivial chances individually, but summed together as \"a new winner,\" the probability is still very low.\n\n**Probability: 6%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
