    "reasoning": "Let me analyze this systematically.\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nToday is May 28, 2026. The deadline is July 1, 2026.\n**Time remaining: 34 days (approximately 5 weeks)**\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nWaymo is currently at 1,044 mi\u00b2 according to Robo Tracker. They need 156 additional qualifying square miles to reach 1,200 mi\u00b2. If nothing changes, the outcome is NO.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- Waymo expands service area at a slower pace than historical trends\n- New service area expansions continue to require waitlists, invited riders, or gradual rollout periods that prevent them from qualifying under Robo Tracker's strict criteria\n- Existing areas don't expand their qualifying footprint significantly\n- Recent service areas (like Miami, Atlanta, Orlando launched in 2024-2025) still operate under limited accessibility that prevents counting\n- Only 100-150 mi\u00b2 of NEW qualifying territory is added in the next 34 days\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- Waymo rapidly expands existing service areas in Phoenix, San Francisco, Austin, or Los Angeles (cities where they already have established operations)\n- One or more new cities launch with immediate public access and full qualifying criteria\n- The $16 billion funding provides momentum for accelerated rollout during this specific window\n- Waymo achieves 156+ mi\u00b2 of NEW qualifying territory before July 1, 2026\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\nHistorical context on Waymo expansion:\n- Waymo has been cautious with expansion, gradually rolling out to new cities\n- Most recent expansions (Miami 2024, Atlanta 2025, Orlando 2025) suggest they're adding 60-90 mi\u00b2 per new city\n- However, these often launch with limited access initially before becoming \"qualifying\"\n- Adding 156 mi\u00b2 in 34 days would represent ~4.6 mi\u00b2 per day of new QUALIFYING territory\n- Waymo's historical pace of adding qualifying terr